<div class="wrapper">

  <section class="content-section">
    <p>
      This glossary explains freestyle footbag terminology: run quality, trick
      components, style, and community vocabulary. It is an explanatory layer
      only. Canonical definitions (ADD values, trick structure, modifier rules)
      live in the freestyle dictionary, not here.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">1. ADD System &amp; Run Quality</h2>
    <p>These terms describe the difficulty of a run, not individual tricks.</p>
    <div class="moves-table-wrap">
      <table class="moves-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Term</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Tiltless</td><td>All tricks in a run are at least 2 ADD.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Guiltless</td><td>All tricks are at least 3 ADD.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Tripless</td><td>All tricks are at least 4 ADD.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Fearless</td><td>All tricks are at least 5 ADD.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Beastly</td><td>All tricks are at least 6 ADD.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Godly</td><td>All tricks are at least 7 ADD.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Genuine</td><td>Guiltless excluding BOP tricks.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>BOP</td><td>Butterfly, Osis, Paradox Mirage.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">2. Core Trick Concepts</h2>

    <h3>ADD (Additional Degree of Difficulty)</h3>
    <p>A scoring system that assigns difficulty values to tricks based on their components.</p>

    <h3>Dexterity (Dex)</h3>
    <p>A motion where the foot circles around the bag.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Mirage uses one dex.</li>
      <li>Double Around the World uses two dexes.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Set</h3>
    <p>The action used to position the bag before a trick.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Uptime</strong>: before the peak.</li>
      <li><strong>Midtime (hangtime)</strong>: at the peak.</li>
      <li><strong>Downtime</strong>: after the peak.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>In modern usage, &ldquo;set&rdquo; refers to the uptime and midtime components.</p>

    <h3>Stall / Delay</h3>
    <p>Controlling the bag on a surface. Examples: toe stall, clipper stall, inside stall. Most stalls are 1 ADD.</p>

    <h3>X-Dex</h3>
    <p>A dexterity performed in a crossed-body position. The Atom Smasher, for example, uses an X-dex.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">3. How Tricks Are Built</h2>
    <p>A trick is typically composed of:</p>
    <pre><code>set &rarr; modifiers &rarr; base &rarr; catch (stall or kick)</code></pre>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Base trick</strong>: the core motion (e.g. mirage, whirl).</li>
      <li><strong>Modifiers</strong>: how the trick is altered (e.g. paradox, spinning).</li>
      <li><strong>Set</strong>: how the trick begins.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Examples:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Paradox Whirl = whirl (base) + paradox (modifier).</li>
      <li>Ripwalk = butterfly (base) + stepping (modifier).</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The glossary explains terms; the dictionary defines exact structure.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">4. Naming &amp; Evolution</h2>
    <p>Freestyle naming evolves over time, and the same trick may carry multiple names.</p>
    <div class="moves-table-wrap">
      <table class="moves-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Older Name</th><th>Modern Name</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Toe Blur</td><td>Quantum Mirage</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Toe Ripwalk</td><td>Quantum Butterfly</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Spyro</td><td>Inspin</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3>Abbreviations</h3>
    <div class="moves-table-wrap">
      <table class="moves-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Abbreviation</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>PS Whirl</td><td>Paradox Symposium Whirl.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>PDX</td><td>Paradox.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>SS</td><td>Same Side.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>Some names persist historically even when structure is identical.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">5. Runs, Combos, and Style</h2>
    <p>These describe how tricks are used, not how they are defined.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Run</strong>: a continuous sequence of tricks.</li>
      <li><strong>Shuffle</strong>: alternating sides rhythmically.</li>
      <li><strong>Link / Transition</strong>: the connection between tricks.</li>
      <li><strong>Connector Trick</strong>: a trick commonly used to maintain flow. Whirl-family tricks often act as connectors.</li>
      <li><strong>Dropless</strong>: a run without drops.</li>
      <li><strong>Density</strong>: average ADD per trick in a run.</li>
      <li><strong>Shred Circle</strong>: a group format where players take turns performing runs.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">6. Play Quality &amp; Style</h2>
    <p>These describe execution quality rather than structure.</p>
    <div class="moves-table-wrap">
      <table class="moves-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Term</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Clean</td><td>Fully controlled, clearly executed.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Sloppy</td><td>Poorly controlled execution.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Thin</td><td>A dex that barely clears the bag.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Slurry</td><td>Dex completed too early; not clean.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Froggy</td><td>Body motion begins before the set completes.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>These do not affect canonical trick definitions.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">7. Notation (Jobs Notation)</h2>
    <p>A symbolic system describing trick structure.</p>
    <pre><code>(clipper) &gt; whirl &gt; butterfly</code></pre>
    <p>This represents the starting surface, intermediate components, and final catch. In this project, notation is stored as text and not yet fully parsed.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">8. Foundational Tricks</h2>
    <p>These are the key primitives that anchor freestyle. Many advanced tricks are built from them.</p>
    <ul class="grid-list">
      <li>clipper</li>
      <li>mirage</li>
      <li>legover</li>
      <li>pickup</li>
      <li>illusion</li>
      <li>whirl</li>
      <li>butterfly</li>
      <li>swirl</li>
      <li>osis</li>
      <li>pixie</li>
      <li>fairy</li>
      <li>around-the-world</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">9. Competitive &amp; Format Terms</h2>
    <p>These describe event formats and play contexts.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Freestyle Routine</strong>: a choreographed performance to music.</li>
      <li><strong>Shred Contest (Shred:30)</strong>: a technical scoring format.</li>
      <li><strong>Big Trick / Sick, Big, Best</strong>: single or combo highlight formats.</li>
      <li><strong>Circle Contest</strong>: a turn-based elimination format.</li>
      <li><strong>Most Rippin&rsquo; Run</strong>: a last-player-standing format.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">10. Attribution</h2>
    <p>Concepts adapted from footbag.org reference materials, freestyle community usage, and expert input from Red Husted. Definitions rewritten for clarity and consistency. The authoritative system lives in the freestyle dictionary.</p>
  </section>

